Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A lunatic asylum where young people are supposed to meet today.
A crypt chapel, where excavations are now taking place for the S-Bahn tunnel.
Small-scale gardeners cultivate the former land of farmers.
The oldest official map of Munich reveals fascinating stories.
It sucks when maps are out of date.
Everyone knows that, who ever had to get upset, because the car sat nav instead of a bypass showed a green meadow.
The historical maps of the digital Bavarian Atlas, an offer of the geoportal Bavaria of the state government, are anything but up-to-date - but for this very reason very informative.
Especially when compared to current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the area of distribution of the Munich Mercury have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavaria atlas is a patchwork that is not immediately recognizable as such.
More detailed maps, so-called urposition sheets, have been incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian Surveying Authority, these originated between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
Their client: Napoleon.
The French army commander occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied land and commissioned a topographical survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even if the French troops eventually withdrew with the Treaty of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the present-day neighbours who came up with the idea of a comprehensive map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV Joseph pushed the project further, founding the "Topographical Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates back to 1856 and, like all others, can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek.
The comparison between past and present is most impressive in the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a district of Munich 21 years after the map was created, i.e. in 1877.
Today Untersendling lies in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendling are concentrated around 1856 along today's Plinganserstraße, which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasant revolt against Austria in 1705.
Where the Westpark is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: when zooming in, a smaller map appears with dozens of lines and numbers: hand-numbered parcels of land from the so-called "primordial recording," from which the property tax was derived.
Today, small plots are no longer occupied by farmers - but by allotment gardeners in the "Land in Sonne" plant.
A large green area can be seen north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, scene of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was in fact still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map provides an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In what is now the district of Au-Haidhausen, not only the street name "am Gasteig" or the hill "Auf der Lüften" can be read in large letters, but also "Irren Anstalt."
Yes, people with delusions were once imprisoned here on Auerfeldstraße.
The Munich mental asylum "Auf der Auer Lüften" was established there in 1858 / 59.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institute - the psychiatrist who is associated with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time, for example, ending the chaining of the so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff from using violence against the inmates, "says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, who has studied the institution for an exhibition.
At first there was room for 280 patients, later on it was extended to 500 places.
Eventually, even this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
On the grounds of the former Auer Anstalt, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with educational establishments.
The TSV München Ost football ground is located to the west and residential buildings from the 1980s to the east.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - architecturally based on the original building of the lunatic asylum, which was destroyed during the Second World War in bombing raids.
The Marienplatz was listed as "Haupt Platz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse."
The Second World War also brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs tore many holes in the city centre in December 1944.
A large one remained to this day - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a crypt chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at Marienhof, where preparatory work and the groundbreaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn main line will take place on 5 April 2017.
