Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is scheduled to take effect August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to pay particular attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable, race-based incidents have recently occurred and are noted throughout the state," the group's statement said.
A recent Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
'You've got civil rights violations that happen to people.
They get stopped because of the color of their skin, they get beaten up or killed, "Missouri NAACP President Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
'We hear complaints with such frequency that we haven't heard them before. '
It is the first such warning issued by the organization for any state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year after running out of gasoline while traveling through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The council also points to a recent report by the Missouri attorney general's office showing that black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely than whites to be stopped.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and let their families, friends and co-workers know what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
'People need to be prepared, whether it's bringing bail money or letting relatives know they're traveling across the state. '
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crimes reporting program, which ranks the state 16th in the country in the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are typically issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, advocacy groups have used the measure in response to specific laws and trends within the United States.
