Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
Americans value them as much as anyone - hence the carefully orchestrated overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration's key ideologues, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to slash legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller did not attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had done so.
But he attacked its meaning, and in particular the meaning attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller scolded Acosta, "I'm not going to go into a whole thing about history, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you refer to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty. "
Miller is factually correct, but as he put it himself, it's not really about history.
It is about the contemporary resonance of Lazarus's stirring words, the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tired, your poor, / your oppressed masses, yearning to breathe freely / the miserable waste of your rich shores."
There has never been a time when the "miserable waste" was more visible on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's America.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural dispute: it is indeed a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who campaigned for her words to be placed at the grassroots after her death - knew full well that they were carrying out a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical figurative representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a very different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of the poem and the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people of the right wing wanted to change it back a long time ago.
The great crier Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative bringing the American flame to the reviled world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
It is to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not meant to illuminate the way to the United States. "
Quite unusually, Limbaugh has come across something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a question of the point of view of perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see it as it was seen by the exhausted, wretched, but hopeful people after long and often terrible voyages on the decks of ships.
It is literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that, of course, is not the perspective Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Her torch is not intended to illuminate the way, but to kindle hatred, which is her only source of power.
