Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand the heat from voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for newspapers to beat him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
He scolded the critics, for sure.
But he has not silenced his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we are led like sheep to slaughter."
That brings me to Maryland Gov. Larry Hogan, who needs to work to be more like Washington.
Hogan's staff have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have voiced their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online comment was full of a backlash with "So what?."
"It's just Facebook," many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state that is astonishingly popular.
He has the second-highest approval rating among the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in running his state and strict adherence to the principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as a primary means of connecting with his constituents and playfully debuting his hairless head on his page after chemotherapy.
Thus, blocking people who come to the governor's side - which is a public forum designated as official, and employees paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than a moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people wielding the whip online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a priest, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not profane.
The pastor cited the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., wasn't hateful, but she did ask about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other breaking news," she wrote in the comments section of The Post.
"I do not like this idea either, when a number of people take a stand on the same issue, some tend to disregard it as a so-called collective effort and not recognise it as a large group of citizens concerned."
What the governor's aides called a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call "advocacy."
The Facebook era makes it easy to tailor a message simply by blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than in the past, if one had done the same, that employees were sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence demonstrators.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for berating Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones on the issue came last week in Virginia.
The chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment when she banned a voter from her Facebook page, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria.
And in Kentucky, Gov. Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU over his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's day, the era of affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers attacked his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people who used pseudonyms such as "Juricola," "Valerius," "Belisarius," and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers that put down Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Amity Treaty, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he hasn't silenced them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are fundamental to our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
