Poverty and death in Indonesia's gold country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she does not use a cooker.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually places a sweet potato - locally called "nota" - directly in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and devoured with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily work, such as washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are the soldiers.
"No one dares walk around the village after 5pm," she says.
It is a rare insight into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was absorbed in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote by public hand before the occupying forces.
An existing pro-independence movement against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control of the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea covering the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is barren, with a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire, followed by a 5-hour morning car ride.
There is no public transport.
The town of about 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs, which have been transformed by rust into various shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made their way here, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes, too.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes," Degei says, pointing to her vibrant, hand-woven turban, dark shirt and light-colored skirt.
"We used to only have leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's goldland.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated $78 billion.
But these riches are a source of misery for the Papuans, who ensure that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in the New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide, according to the Asia Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful demonstrators last year.
"We will lose everything," says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which included accounts of atrocities from the previous year, including unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week," said Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have tightened as Papua's resources bring in an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese Warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to keep up.
"The migrants have started selling chickens and vegetables cheaper than local Papuans in the traditional market," said Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital, Jayapura, for work.
"It cost the indigenous Papuans - the Mama-Mama [the women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to tackle inequalities and rights abuses in Papua.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's 29 districts - including Paniai - on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored," You said.
Indeed, just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October, Paniai hit rock bottom.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols in front of a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke through the darkness.
The terrified children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offence at her tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers who had been drinking chased and beat the group with the butts of their rifles, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire, and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papua men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird song - by Papua's Mee Pago tribe.
Some demonstrators began throwing stones at police and military posts.
As the mood heated up, soldiers were sent an order over an internal radio: "If the masses resist more than three times, they shoot them dead," according to an official document obtained by TIME, which was not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood of Enarotali, saw the threat and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired, but says the bullet came from the ranks of soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, lots of shots were fired," he added.
Local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shootings.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, who like many Indonesians has only one name, told TIME in a somber mood.
'I saw he was dead... I kissed him, 'she said.
The Chief Inspector of Papua New Guinea Police, Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers only wanted to "secure" her station because she was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua Police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
'It's a matter of life and death. '
According to Human Rights Watch, five young demonstrators were killed and many others injured.
News of the killings only came 'filtered' to Jakarta the following day.
