Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
In addition, restrictions on international media coverage remain tense.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua due to lack of coordination with related institutions, despite being given rare permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi's campaign's promises to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development have not materialized.
"There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to cover Indonesia's troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua: visa denial and a blacklist," he said in a statement.
A lack of press control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government remains largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands - called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
