In 1267 the chapel of St. Hilary was mentioned for the first time in the Wuerttemberg document book: Count Hermann von Sulz sold "the mountain with the parish church in Tumlingen including the bailiff's office" to Magister Eberhard von Horb and to his brother Dietrich for 20 Mark silver.
In addition to the former parish church, according to the text of the document, there was also a manorial courtyard on Tumlinger Berg, to which the church or the right of patronage belonged, and not vice versa.
So there were people living there.
As can be seen from the description of the upper office of Freudenstadt from 1858, besides the lower village and the upper village, which are still barely recognizable in the townscape of Tumlingen, the "mountain" was the third, the noble settlement core of the village.
Old maps from around the year 1600 support these historical facts.
The right of patronage arose from early medieval canon law.
A gentleman who built, furnished and occupied a church with a priest remained the owner of this church and could also inherit this church.
Linked to this was the right to appoint a pastor or to propose a new pastor to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
The larger of the two broke up on Christmas Day 1673.
The newly purchased bell sounded for the first time in 1692, but had to be surrendered later in the Second World War in 1942.
