The roof was leaking.
In 1796, French troops camped near the church.
They broke out the pulpit and church chairs and used them as firewood.
Remains of the church threatened to collapse in 1809.
Until 1869, the Hilarius cemetery in Tumlingen also served as the final resting place for the dead from Hörschweiler.
In 1823 the cemetery was enlarged and the church of St. Hilary was demolished.
Only the steeple was left standing.
On New Year's Eve 1834, a storm split the steeple and half of it collapsed.
In order to prevent an accident, the tower was demolished.
Only the tower dwarf that still exists today has been preserved as a witness to the 750-year-old history of the church.
Today Horst Kallenberger and Rolf-Dieter Wasem from the "Schaffigen Pensionern" are taking care of the Hilarius plant as successors to Dieter Dockhorn.
