New Results of Swedish Asylum Age Assessment Tests Published
The latest results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have been subjected to a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80% of the people tested are older than 18, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started carrying out the tests last year.
During the asylum procedure, they are to make the assessment of age more precise, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were underage.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent out 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under the age of 18."
The tests will only be carried out in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics over the past few months, the numbers are pretty constant," he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his or her age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases that "suggest the person being examined is 18 years or older."
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases, the person had openly said that he would turn 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then analysed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticised in some areas.
One skeptic is the Karolinska Institute's endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing people's biological maturity to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
'I had reason to think about it and I don't think the type of measurement should be used.
Assessing the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can, "he told Metro newspaper.
But Göransson, from the Forensic Medicine Agency, defended the accuracy of the tests, saying: "In general, you can say that the risk of judging a child incorrectly as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is if the person is just under 18, in this case it's about 10 per cent. '
