Together with the Bulgarian trumpeter Miroslav Petkov he gives a concert under the motto "Black Sea meets Black Forest," or "Balkan folklore" meets a classical German education with roots in brass music.
Both soloists are winners and prize winners of numerous international competitions and have held solo positions in top European orchestras.
Petkov is principal trumpeter with the renowned Concertgebouw Orchestra Amsterdam and Frederic Belli is principal trombonist with the SWR Symphony Orchestra.
Both share the desire not only to transcend the boundaries of their instruments, but also to merge the boundaries of the different genres.
Thus Johann Sebastian Bach can be heard in both of them as if in a new guise, Daniel Schnyder's "World Music" unites with Bulgarian folklore, and in the piece "Exchange Suite" by jazz echo prize winner Nils Wogram, classical music, jazz and free play blend into a fascinating Gesamtkunstwerk.
This centrepiece of the programme was premiered only this spring in Freiburg with enormous success.
The renowned composer Nils Wogram wrote it especially for the two musicians and even more: the Haslach monastery church with its special acoustics is consciously included in the concert.
Kristen Stewart talks about her bisexuality
"Some people love grilled cheese and will eat it until the end of their lives.
But I want to try everything, "Kristen Stewart said candidly about her bisexuality.
"Once I bite into grilled cheese, I think," Oh that was cool, what's next? ""
Arguably the Hollywood star's best-known relationship was with her "Twilight" co-star Robert Pattinson, which ultimately fell apart bitterly.
Despite this, the brunette actress told Harper's Bazaar magazine: 'I was genuinely in love with everyone I dated.
Or do you think I played it? "
After their split, Kristen admitted that she was bisexual: 'I've always lived the dualism and genuinely believed in it.
So it has never baffled or hindered me.
I just never liked not being taken seriously. "
According to "Bang Showbiz," however, she suffered most from this during her school days, when she preferred to dress like a boy: "Not all girls are typical girls.
It really hurt me a lot.
When I was eleven, the children told me I looked like a boy.
I felt really attacked, scared and ashamed.
