She doesn't like to explain her love life to the public in particular: "People expect you to behave in a certain way and that annoys me.
And maybe some people call me ungrateful, but I don't like having to justify myself in front of the whole public. '
West Virginia Governor Announces He's Changing Party
Democratic West Virginia Governor Jim Justice announced Thursday night at a rally with President Trump that he would switch parties.
Like it or not, the Democrats have moved away from me, "Governor Justice said.
'Today I'm going to tell you with a lot of prayers and a lot of reflection... today I'm going to tell you as a West Virginia resident I can't help you anymore when I'm a Democratic governor. '
The rally erupted in cheers.
"Tomorrow I will change my registration to the Republicans," Justice added.
'As a coach, I'd say it's time to play a different game. '
Mr. Trump earlier promised a big announcement at the West Virginia rally.
Mr. Trump won West Virginia by 42 points, and Justice did not endorse Democratic nominee Hillary Clinton.
Justice, who according to Forbes is the only billionaire in the state, was elected in 2016.
Forbes notes that he owns coal mines in five states and inherited a coal business from his father.
He is worth about $1.59 billion.
Meanwhile, the Republican National Committee issued a statement Thursday night saying, "Governor Justice's change of party is another blow to a Democratic Party that would rather hinder than work to make our country great again."
"With only 15 governorships and control of the fewest legislative bodies in history, Governor Justice's announcement is just the latest rejection of a party that is top-to-bottom without leadership and unable to find a positive, unifying message," RNC Chairwoman Ronna McDaniel said in a statement to CBS News.
Coe praises' honest 'Russian apology for doping scandal
World athletics chief Sebastian Coe on Thursday praised what he described as a blatant apology from Russia over a doping scandal, but reiterated it was not the time for the country to return to the sport.
Russia's athletics chief Dmitry Shylakhtin said at the IAAF congress on the eve of the World Athletics Championships that his country's banishment from the sport was correct and that he was determined to fight doping.
He said he felt sorry for "all the athletes who have had their gold and silver medals snatched away in competitions."
Despite his comments, the IAAF Congress voted to uphold the ban, which was imposed in November 2015 after a World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) report found evidence of state-sponsored doping in Russia.
"I thought it was a very open answer today, a very honest presentation," IAAF president Coe told reporters.
"The entire Council and the entire Congress were pleased that the Russian Federation has recognized in itself that it has experienced some pretty hot times and will do everything possible to ensure that the Federation is reshaped."
Coe said he was also "pleased" that Russia accepted the criteria for its reinstatement.
"I think it was a very constructive day and I think progress has been made, but Congress supports the task force's recommendations that this is not the time to reinstate Russia," Coe said.
"We must do everything in the next few months to normalise this situation.
The guiding principle has always been that we want to separate clean athletes from the tainted system, "he added.
Nineteen Russian athletes will compete as neutral players under the strict IAAF criteria at the World Athletics Championships, which begin in London on Friday.
The head of the IAAF task force, Rune Andersen, said on Monday that Russia had yet to meet some of the criteria for reinstatement.
Drug testing is still inadequate and banned coaches are still operating freely, he told reporters in London after a presentation to the IAAF Council.
Funeral for soldiers killed in Mali
At a funeral service in Fritzlar in northern Hesse, around 1,000 people paid tribute to the two soldiers who died in a helicopter crash in Mali.
The ceremony took place on Thursday in the cathedral city under high security.
Defence Minister Ursula von der Leyen (CDU) said nothing about the still unexplained cause of the crash.
But she described the two pilots who died as "experts in their field."
"We bow before this supreme sacrifice that they have made on behalf of the Federal Republic of Germany," she said.
The 33-year-old major and the 47-year-old chief of staff from northern Hesse were killed in Mali, West Africa, a week ago on Wednesday.
Their coffins were transported to Germany and on Thursday, accompanied by a funeral vigil of the Bundeswehr, they were brought to the Cathedral of St. Peter in Fritzl.
At midday, only the relatives in the church said goodbye.
Afterwards, the funeral service began in the circle of family, closest friends, representatives of the Bundeswehr as well as politicians.
Among them were the Prime Minister of Hessen Volker Bouffier (CDU) and the Inspector General of the Bundeswehr Volker Wieker.
Mourners laid roses and relatives stood arm in arm by the coffins.
In front of the church, Fritzlarer and numerous soldiers watched the ceremony on a screen.
Defence Minister von der Leyen described the soldiers who died as "highly decorated" and experienced.
The chief of staff helped to build up the flying operations of the Tiger combat helicopter in Fritzlar and was one of the first six trained Tiger pilots of his regiment.
Volker Bauersachs, commander of the regiment to which the soldiers belong, also declared: "If this crew could not avert the crash, then no one would have been able to."
Minister von der Leyen showed no doubts about the UN mission in Mali: the operation was dangerous.
But it is also of great importance "for a country from which we are only separated by two states," she said.
After the funeral service, the coffins were taken out of the cathedral.
The Bundeswehr did not specify when or where they will be buried.
Prince Henrik doesn't want a grave next to his wife
The husband of Danish Queen Margrethe (77), Prince Henrik (83), does not want to be buried next to his wife after his death.
The royal family announced the news on Thursday.
Traditionally, the Danish royal couple is buried in Roskilde Cathedral.
The sculptor Bjørn Nørgaard has already made a sarcophagus for the two.
The Queen agreed with her husband's decision, the statement added.
It is not yet clear where Prince Henrik will be buried.
But he had no intention of being buried in his native France.
Prince Henrik had never made any secret of the fact that he was not happy with his title.
After the accession to the throne of his wife Margrethe in 1972, he would have liked to become king.
He retired in 2016 and also holds the title of "Prince Consort."
Since Henrik did not get the title and function he wanted in Denmark, he did not consider himself equal to his wife - even after death, explained Lene Balleby, the chief spokeswoman of the Danish royal family.
It is not yet clear where the 83-year-old's final resting place will ultimately be.
However, he did not intend to be buried in his French homeland, but in Denmark.
He likes the country he has worked for over the past 50 years.
Born Henri de Laborde de de Monpezat, the son of a French noble family, Margrethe had met in London in 1965.
He worked in the French Embassy on the River Thames.
While his later wife always received the sympathies of the people, Prince Henrik had a hard time in his nearly 50-year reign with the Danes.
In an autobiography, Henrik said of his first years in Denmark: "A few months after my arrival, everything I did was criticised.
My Danish was fluctuating, I preferred wine instead of beer, silk stockings instead of knitted socks, Citroën instead of Volvo, tennis instead of football.
Even for the Gauloises I smoked instead of Virginia tobacco, who had a reputation in this country for being the brand of socially critical intellectuals, I could not hope for leniency.
I was different.
I seemed to be happy with this position and not ashamed.
That was two mistakes! "
Prime Minister Weil wants early elections
CDU and FDP facing possible majority in Lower Saxony
Lower Saxony's Prime Minister Stephan Weil (SPD) is in favour of a quick new election of the state parliament after the loss of the red-green government majority, but he does not want to resign.
Weil called for parliament to be dissolved on Friday.
Earlier, the surprise resignation of a Green MP from her parliamentary group in Lower Saxony plunged the government of Prime Minister Stephan Weil (SPD) into a serious crisis.
Five months before the official date of the state election, the red-green coalition in Hanover thus lost its narrow one-vote majority in parliament to the opposition from the CDU and FDP.
The previous Green MP Elke Twesten justified her move by not being nominated for the 2018 election in her constituency in Rotenburg (Wümme).
"I see my political future in the CDU," she said in Hanover on Friday.
CDU parliamentary group leader Björn Thümler wants to recommend his group to accept them.
Together, the CDU and FDP would have 69 seats in the Lower Saxony state parliament, the SPD and the Greens 68 seats.
So far, the relationship has been reversed.
The new state parliament will be elected on 14 January next year.
Thümler said that the red-green state government must now decide whether it can continue to govern in this situation without a majority.
Stephan Weil considers it indispensable, however, that the state parliament decides on its self-dissolution as soon as possible.
The CDU parliamentary group is expected to decide on its next course of action on Tuesday.
The state constitution also provides for the possibility that the state parliament removes the Prime Minister's confidence and elects a successor.
"Our Constitution offers several options.
These possibilities must be properly examined in legal terms, "said Thümler.
"All issues will be discussed calmly when they have been examined in a legally reasonable manner."
Thümler called Twesten's move "a bit odd."
The politician herself insisted: "I am not a traitor.
I'm feeling very good. '
She described herself as a follower of black and green.
The Greens called on the renegade MP to return her parliamentary mandate.
"We naturally assume that she will return her parliamentary mandate, which she received via the Green Land List, with immediate effect," announced the chairmen of the Länder Meta Janssen-Kucz and Stefan Körner.
The leader of the Green Party Anja Piel said: "We deeply regret Elke Twesten's decision."
She had made a conscious decision not to have a debate within the group.
"Even against the background that there were no substantive differences, we cannot understand this step."
SPD candidate for chancellor Martin Schulz condemns the conversion of Lower Saxony Green MP Elke Twesten to the CDU as a betrayal.
"The behaviour of the former Green MPs in Lower Saxony is not only a betrayal of voters, but also a betrayal of the Red-Green Party," the leader of the Social Democrats wrote on Facebook on Friday.
He supported the decision of Prime Minister Stephan Weil (SPD) to have the state parliament re-elected quickly.
Leaving the EU will cost the Tories a majority in Lower Saxony.
The politician put "in her wounded vanity and in her frustration her personal interests before the welfare of the country," criticized SPD Secretary General Hubertus Heil.
"It is scandalous that the CDU in Lower Saxony is taking part in this dirty game of intrigue and is trying to make political capital out of it."
Lower Saxony's CDU parliamentary group leader Björn Thümler wants to recommend to his deputies that Elke Twesten join the CDU.
The parliamentary group leader of the SPD in the Bundestag, Thomas Oppermann, accused Twesten of distorting the result of the 2013 state election with personal career thinking.
At that time, the CDU was the strongest force before the SPD, but the SPD and the Greens had a wafer-thin one-vote majority in the state parliament.
Interview with Agriculture Minister - How do we protect ourselves from poisonous eggs, Mr Schmidt?
Germany discusses contaminated eggs.
How did the scandal happen?
How can consumers protect themselves?
Agriculture Minister Christian Schmidt (CSU) answers questions in an interview with the RedaktionsNetzwerk Deutschland (RND).
Mr Schmidt, how can consumers protect themselves from poisoned eggs?
I can only encourage all consumers to take a close look at the eggs in your fridge and check the stamp.
On the consumer protection portal www.Lebensmittelwarnung.de, the federal states provide the latest information on the egg batches concerned.
Affected eggs should be destroyed or returned.
Even if, as far as we know at present, there is virtually no risk to health.
Is Aldi now adopting the best possible crisis response - taking all eggs out of the supply - because the Federal Minister of Agriculture is not really taking on the central role of enlightenment?
Food monitoring is the task of the federal states.
Nevertheless, my House intervened immediately and has been in close contact with the authorities of the Länder ever since the news of Germany's concern became known.
All information and the risk assessment are available to consumers.
Retailers, like manufacturers, must ensure that the products sold are marketable and harmless to health.
If eggs exceed the maximum residue level of 0.005 mg / kg, they are not marketable.
However, uncontaminated eggs can be sold and eaten.
This time, it is not the farms that are to blame.
Are production companies and consumers in the same boat?
As far as we know, there is no direct culpability on the part of the production companies.
On the contrary, they face economic damage as a result of alleged illegal practices by service companies.
As always, there are too few controllers in an emergency.
Is there only a lack of staff or a lack of coherent competence?
After all, it was the official controls that uncovered the affair.
But the truth is that food fraud and criminal energy can never be 100 per cent ruled out.
Precisely for this reason, a consistent investigation of such events and handing them over to the public prosecutor's office in cases where criminal offences may be committed are of crucial importance.
I have already made it clear on several occasions that I expect the responsible authorities to provide a full explanation.
Is regular alarmism in food scandals really necessary?
Consumers have the right to receive only safe and marketable food.
Consumers are right to be outraged when an unauthorised insecticide is used in the food industry.
The adulterated agent has put manufacturers, distributors and consumers in a situation that is absolutely unnecessary.
In principle, it must be clear that the illegal use of the insecticide fipronil in the keeping of food-producing animals is unacceptable and must be stopped immediately.
This needs to be worked on consistently and at full speed at all levels.
I expect all the competent authorities to clarify the situation quickly and without gaps.
How football's financial rules are affecting Neymar's move to Paris
The rules, aimed at preventing unfettered spending by European football clubs, will not interfere with Neymar's world-record transfer from Barcelona in Spain to Paris Saint Germain in France.
Any consequences for Paris Saint-Germain will still come from UEFA, because the governing body that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from entering the prestigious Champions League tournament.
Financial fair play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 mean PSG will eventually have to prove that Neymar's transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona have paid 222 million euros ($262 million) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract and Neymar will receive a salary in the region of tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG can certainly make the money to sign Neymar and take him to a galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money to acquire players, but they have to counteract this with legitimate revenue streams that allow them to break even in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after he was elected UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had taken on huge debts in their quest for success were effectively cheating and risked ruining themselves if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from focusing on clubs "debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich initially used at Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the squad and build a global brand - was to become a harder business.
During the current three-year FFP investment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can incur losses of €30m.
And although Platini fell from grace as president in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin remains committed to discouraging excessive spending.
"FFP is certainly not dead and we will certainly strengthen the rules going forward," Andrea Traverso, UEFA's head of FFP, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar's buy-out clause as a lump sum, they can spread the amount over the length of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, meaning the transfer fee for the next five years of €44.4m will be included in the annual accounts.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 hit PSG, along with Abu Dhabi, which is owned by Manchester City, with the heaviest sanctions.
PSG received a fine of 60 million euros (then 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and it was ordered that the team members for the 2014-15 Champions League season be limited to 21 players instead of the normal 25.
UEFA is looking for clubs that might try to outwit its financial regulator by inflating their revenues through companies linked to the owners of a club.
While a Qatari company could sponsor PSG if the value of the sponsorship exceeded the standard market rates, UEFA would not consider this a legitimate income.
That is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of PSA sponsorship had been inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It has been reported that part of PSG's payments to Neymar could come via payments from Qatar's 2022 World Cup organising committee.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become a World Cup ambassador and such a manoeuvre could be easy for UEFA regulators to figure out.
The sanctions against PSG so far mean UEFA will be even more vigilant to any attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA had no preliminary talks with PSG over Neymar's transfer, said people familiar with the situation on Thursday.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss the PSG situation.
The most recent published reports show PSG made a profit of more than €10m in 2015 / 16 on revenues of €542.4m.
The accounts for the last financial year have yet to be published.
PSG expect Neymar's arrival to be a boon for sponsorship deals, merchandising and shirt sales.
The club expects turnover to increase by at least 30 per cent after the signing.
The Spanish league were clearly irritated to see one of football's best players leave and tried to block Neymar's departure by claiming that PSG would violate FFP.
"It is a clear case of 'financial doping' with the club and the state," La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish daily AS, referring to Qatar's eventual ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's reservations about a state funding a club.
"It is the consequence of ownership and that has completely changed the whole landscape of football over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"As soon as a country owns a club, anything is possible.
It will be very difficult to respect financial fair play because you can go down different paths or have different interests when a country has such a big player to represent a country. "
Swiss is looking for a new chocolate supplier
In recent years, Chocolat Frey has produced on-board chocolate for Swiss.
Now the sweet collaboration is about to come to an end: The airline is re-tendering the contract.
At the request of the news agency sda, Swiss spokeswoman Meike Fuhlrott confirmed a corresponding report by the newspaper "Nordwestschweiz" on Friday.
According to current plans, the airline will conclude a new contract in the first half of 2018.
The products would be checked every two to three years and subjected to quality control.
"We are very satisfied with the current supplier Chocolat Frey," the spokeswoman said.
Approximately 17 million small red-and-white chocolate bars of 14 grams are distributed to passengers each year by the flight attendants before landing.
Swiss declined to give details about the costs.
