Nostalgia Goes Niche in "Wet Hot American Summer" and "Comrade Detective"
This rerun of history is simultaneously nostalgic for the glory days of the characters of the 1980s, for the grunge era of the 1990s (when masterminds David Wain and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy "The State" for MTV), and for itself - that is, for 2001, before its stars, such as Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, and Paul Rudd, went to greater things.
As a cultural artifact, it is both a parody and an embodiment of our Facebook-enabled era of permanent memories.
But as a franchise, it feels like time is running out.
"First Day of Camp" worked surprisingly well, and not just because of its absurd humor (it included an original story for a talking can of vegetables spoken by H. Jon Benjamin).
By sticking to the core of the gags - middle-aged actors play horny kids who grow up - they still managed to win back the last part of the joke.
"Ten Years Later," with its grown-ups now playing adults, is less emotionally rooted and its parody is more watered-down, including a riff on the stalker movies of the 1990s such as "The Hand That Rocks the Cradle."
At one point, a character rummages through an Apple Powerbook, some inline skates, and "a bunch of other things from 1991."
Many of the central stories are the same.
The amiable Coop (Mr. Showalter), now a novelist, still hasn't forgotten Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn't lost his virginity.
And there's another crazily malicious plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Mr. Showalter), now backed by George H. W. Bush (a good impression of Michael Ian Black).
As always, the digressions are the best part of the franchise.
It's especially fun to see the eternally young Mr. Rudd showing Matt Dillon's "Singles" lip-beard, whose former big-man-on-camp Andy now feels like an old cracker.
It's the moments of random madness that could fuel this franchise like some kind of repetitive "Seven Up!" series until it reaches what I assume is its logical conclusion: "Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later," the final scene of which will show the gang attending the film premiere of "Wet Hot American Summer."
"Comrade Detective" on Amazon now evokes a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War revival of "The Americans," the movie "Atomic Blonde," and even "GLOW," with its East-versus-West wrestling iconography.
Created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka, this comedy, directed by Rhys Thomas, claims to be a found TV series: an eighties Romanian drama with the two policemen as friends, two officers from Bucharest, fighting for truth, atheism and the path of Marxism-Leninism.
The main characters - a hard-boiled Gregor and an idealistic Iosef - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Corneliu Ulici, whose dialogues are dubbed in English by Channing Tatum (also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a brilliant idea.
But it's not much more than an idea.
There are some nice gags to watch (the police spend their time watching chess on TV, as Americans might do with football).
And the list of famous speakers - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny - makes for a decent 'find the voice' game.
But "Comrade Detective" is so committed to the veracity of a desperate propaganda drama - involving a murderer wearing a Reagan mask - that it often plays like one.
Six long episodes drag on, and the comedy is not fast or frequent enough.
"Comrade Detective," which has been edited to a lesser length, could better deliver its agitprop satire, as Gregor and Iosef keep visiting the American Embassy, whose lobby is always occupied by two fat men devouring a pile of hamburgers.
The message for the imagined communist audience is that Western culture can make anything fodder for a feast.
The fictional Romanian creators were not wrong: we even do it with our own recent history and theirs.
Blow to the country's drug mafia
The police have dealt a blow to the Italian mafia in Baden-Württemberg.
On Wednesday morning, numerous objects were searched in the Schwarzwald-Baar-Kreis, Rottweil, Konstanz, Esslingen and Stuttgart, the prosecutor's office in Konstanz announced on Friday.
Fifteen suspects, aged between 25 and 77, were arrested and arrest warrants have already been issued for them.
Officers also seized large quantities of marijuana and cocaine, firearms and several hundred thousand euros.
Two people have been arrested in simultaneous raids in Italy.
German arrest warrants were issued for the two suspects.
The two are therefore likely to be extradited to Germany.
Italian and Bavarian investigators were involved in the operation.
In total, more than 300 police officers were deployed.
The members of the mafia are accused of organised drug crime, serious violence, attempted murder, robbery and extortion.
The prosecutor's office in Konstanz has been investigating organized drug trafficking in southern Germany since the summer of 2016.
There was a lively exchange between the prosecutors in Konstanz and Palermo and the investigators of the Rottweil police station had almost daily contact with their colleagues in Sicily.
That is why four officials from Palermo accompanied the large-scale operation on Wednesday morning.
The investigation focused on Italian nationals with close ties to the Italian mafia.
An incident on 27 May in Hüfingen, in which several shots were fired into a restaurant early in the morning, is also likely to be attributed to the gang.
Weise complains of large gaps in the foreigner register
"Data of citizens who should not show up": According to a report, the register of foreigners in Germany has significant shortcomings.
This sometimes leads to serious miscarriages of justice in asylum proceedings.
According to a media report, the Federal Government Commissioner for Refugee Management, Frank-Jürgen Weise, has drawn attention to large gaps in the Central Register of Foreigners.
Deficiencies in the data registered there could lead to "sometimes serious wrong decisions" in asylum procedures and deportations, Weise warned in an analysis published in the "Süddeutsche Zeitung."
According to the figures, the register covers ten million people with foreign nationality, including around 5.7 million from non-EU countries.
According to this, the data is administered by around 600 immigration authorities in Germany.
Because the data had not been sufficiently maintained, the data quality had not been good in parts until now.
In individual cases, data from 1921 were found, "of people who have long since ceased to be alive, or of citizens who have become German citizens and should no longer appear in the register."
"Incorrect data entry can significantly slow return processes," the report says.
In addition, the statistics on people who are obliged to leave the country include EU citizens who do not have to leave the country at all.
Such misallocations, however, "led to a distorted debate about how to deal with those who are obliged to leave," the analysis said.
Meanwhile, the German government appears to have begun to send refugee families with children under 16 back to Italy when they have entered from there.
This is apparent from an internal paper by the Federal Office for Migration and Refugees (BAMF), reports the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung."
According to the paper, the BAMF has been carrying out such procedures "with regard to families with children - with the exception of infants and very young children - in Italy since 1 June 2017."
Since the end of 2014, this has been practically impossible, according to the newspaper, referring to the difficult situation on the ground.
Under the Dublin Agreement, refugees are the responsibility of the EU state they reach first.
If a migrant continues to travel to another EU country, that country can send him back to the country of entry.
In justifying the decision, the Office wrote: "In the meantime, the reception capacity for families with minor children in Italy has increased considerably."
Italy has given guarantees for the reception and accommodation of families.
Even the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) considers these assurances sufficient.
Other EU states would also send refugees back there under the Dublin Agreement.
The home affairs spokeswoman of the Left faction in the Bundestag, Ulla Jelpke, criticised the decision: "Families with children are threatened with human rights violations and endangering the welfare of children because of the deficiencies in the Italian asylum system."
