Antarctica: Giant iceberg floats in Antarctica
In West Antarctica, a gigantic iceberg nearly seven times the size of Berlin has detached from the ice shelf.
This was announced by the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research in Bremerhaven on Wednesday.
The colossus, which weighs over one trillion tons and measures 5800 square kilometres, is now drifting north and will probably take two or three years to melt.
With a length of 175 kilometres and a width of up to 50 kilometres, it is one of the largest ice giants that researchers have registered in the past three decades.
He does not pose a danger to people.
The extent to which climate change played a role in breaking the iceberg is unclear, according to researchers.
Overall, however, there has been a series of unusual collapses of ice shelves in the region for about 30 years, the US Research Center for Snow and Ice (NSIDC) writes in a fact sheet.
Many researchers believe this could be linked to global warming.
The colossus that has now broken off was previously part of the Larsen C ice shelf.
Ice shelves float on the sea and are fed by large glaciers.
It therefore grows further and further into the sea and breaks off regularly.
The Larsen C ice shelf is located south of South America almost at the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
North of this ice shelf, the balance of growth and breaking was disturbed a few years ago.
A complete ice shelf has disintegrated there, writes AWI researcher Daniela Jansen.
There is some evidence that the Larsen C ice shelf is also at risk, as the front edge has never retreated as far as it is at present.
In addition, the ice sheet is under tension and could disintegrate if a piece breaks off at a key point.
The melting of ice shelves and icebergs does not raise sea levels, because they float on water and ice displaces as much water as it results from the melting itself.
However, the loss of the ice shelf means that the glaciers flow directly into the sea and can drain much faster than before.
This could possibly raise sea levels, but only to a small extent, according to the British Antarctic Observation Project (Midas).
The Larsen C ice shelf is the fourth largest in Antarctica, covering almost 50,000 square kilometres, according to AWI.
At the transition from the mainland it is up to 700 meters thick, at the leading edge to the open ocean about 200 meters.
There it breaks off regularly.
"Although it is a natural event and we are not aware of any direct link to climate change, the ice sheet is now in a more vulnerable position," said Martin O'Leary of Swansea University in the UK.
"This is the furthest retreat since records began," he said.
Scientists are debating whether the Larsen C ice shelf will grow again or shrink over the long term and possibly collapse, said his colleague Adrian Luckman, adding: "Our models say it will be less stable."
But this development will take decades.
Even if these researchers do not attribute the break-off of this gigantic iceberg to climate change, a large number of ice shelves on the Antarctic Peninsula have disintegrated in recent decades.
This long strip of Antarctica stretches towards South America.
According to data from the British Antarctic Survey, the Antarctic Peninsula's ice cover has shrunk by 28,000 square kilometres since the 1950s.
The rise in temperature had contributed to the decline.
The Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by around three degrees Celsius over the past 50 years, making it one of the areas where temperatures are rising the fastest.
