The killing of a journalist underscores the growing threat in Mexico
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to review their plans for reporting on the recent chaos in the state of Sinaloa caused by organized crime, corrupt officials and incessant drug wars.
But that day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to talk about safety.
They were told it was important to change their routines.
Two senior journalists discuss what feels safer: taking their children into the office, who were the target of a grenade attack in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a board at the front of the room: enemies, neutrals, allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column - no proof is needed, perceptions and gut feelings are enough.
There are drug smugglers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being on the payroll of the government or cartels, a catalogue of criminals who make the chaos of Mexico dangerous.
There is no lull from the violence, and while bodies are piling up all over the country, there are more and more journalists: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012. 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats, and so far this year there have been at least seven deaths in seven states.
Among the latter is its editor and inspiration of Riodoce, the co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His absence is deeply felt, even though his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdez with his middle finger emblazoned with the word "Justice" hangs on the façade of the Riodoce building. Two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that show his smiling face with glasses or his trademark Panama hat.
The workshop takes place less than two months after his death, and the reporters discuss their shared themes, trauma, nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was established in 2010 to handle journalists "cases, it has opened only two criminal cases, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organized crime each year, journalists "killers are rarely brought to justice.
In Riodoce, they still insist on dealing with the violence of Sinaloa, even though they are inconsolable and the terrain is even more treacherous now.
Without information about the killers, without justice, the meeting to discuss security has little use, Ibarra says.
"It's very stupid to waste my time in this workshop," he says.
'As long as we don't know the why, we distrust everyone. '
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the office of the newspaper Riodoce in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men. He was forced out of his car and shot 12 times, presumably because of the newspaper's name - which translates as "Twelfth River."
The gunman drove away in his car and damaged it nearby.
Valdez was 50.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumors tend to fly freely around Culiacan.
But on the Valdez issue, there is practically nothing but silence.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions here fight to fill the vacuum.
It does not matter that every day in Sinaloa one or more people are shot in the street, or that the cemetery is full of decorated, two-story mausoleums for drug lords that are larger than many houses for the living.
Forget for a minute that there is a state of "calm" when only one cartel has control over the coastal state, with its valuable ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
Nevertheless, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez (60), a co-founder and director of Riodoce, is broken with guilt for not being able to protect his friend.
He believes two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First came the release in February of an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival cartel factions at war with Guzman's sons.
The publication may have angered the sons, with suspected gang members buying up every copy of the issue as soon as it was delivered to newsstands.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a milestone in Mexican violence against journalists.
He had survived for so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be there.
He was an experienced reporter for Noroeste in 2003 when he teamed up with five colleagues to found Riodoce and sold $50 stakes.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without coming across the drug problem," Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for its courageous and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved to be able to publish hard-hitting investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by a publication in which they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after Riodoce was founded, she received the prestigious "Maria Moors Cabot Prize" for her coverage in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in pursuing Mexican drug history wherever it led.
He voluntarily admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to live on," he said at the time of the CPJ award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa "is a way of life," he said last October in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
'You've got to do the job that you do as a journalist - either that or you play the fool.
I don't want to be asked: "What did you do in the face of so many dead... why didn't you say what was going on?"
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the joker who could curse like a docker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit at the same table.
Now they ask: Was his love of routine his undoing?
His death has also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their job and stay alive.
"You don't like it when you're dealing with their wives, their children, their clean shops, their secret runways" to move drugs.
"These things were not allowed," Bojorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, is a high degree of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trust your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble is, said the editor of Riodoce Andres Villarreal, that "smell is a sense that can be deceived... and then the thing happened with Javier."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - just as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero, and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions, and corrupt government officials.
