Dinosaur used camouflage to evade his enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Now researchers have discovered that the first findings of a Canadian miner's incredible rhino have been so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they could even see that his scaly skin was reddish brown - and they said she had something of a "troubled past."
The report in the journal Current Biology called it "the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found, and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has baffled researchers, who describe it as' truly remarkable'
According to reports in National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk as he was digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He encountered something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal inside the 2,500 pound (1,100kg) lump of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
"If you just blink your eyes a little bit, you could almost believe it was asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
"It will go down in science history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
Researchers have found that although this herbivore is covered in armour and resembles a walking armour, it was probably threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armoured dinosaur used a red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a shielding technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend better into its surroundings and evade its enemies, experts say, suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family made headlines for the first time in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that has spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The astonishing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor over his body.
They discovered countershading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, meaning the creature's top was darker than its underside.
Although countershading is common, the results are surprising, as the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of today's animals.
It suggests that the dinosaur was chased by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored concealing confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that use countershading - think deer, zebras, or armadillos - are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, signaling that this nodosaur was facing a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous must have been," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists are continuing to examine the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was driven out to sea, where it sank on its back to the seabed.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is really remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, but it is also preserved in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous period.
You don't have to use much imagination to reconstruct it. If you just squint your eyes a little, you might almost think he's sleeping. "
The Cretaceous was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that stood on two legs, crisscrossed the earth.
Although the king of them, Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors.
They include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 m) long, six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Current Biology, believe Borealopelta sank into the sea after death and was mummified in the mud.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk as he was digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is complete from muzzle to hip.
The creatures were on average about 18 feet (5 meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
It contained two 20-inch-long spikes that protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe the armored herbivore washed up across western Canada until a flooded river flooded it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover bumpy armor plates along the dinosaur
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, such a level of conservation is as' rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it gets.
Petrified remains of the skin still cover the bumpy armor plates that carry the animal's skull.
His right front foot is on his side, his five fingers are splayed upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole. '
