Deutsche Bahn: Group tests "comfort check-in"
It is a moment that almost everyone has experienced before: You sit on the train and sleep unsuspecting.
Or you are engrossed in your work and just have a brilliant thought.
And then: pufff.
If the conductor comes and rudely wakes you up or pulls the passenger out of the workflow.
Ticket inspection.
But the days of interruptions are soon over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing creator-less ticket control.
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and thus validate the ticket.
There is currently a test operation on two lines.
"When the offer arrives, we expand it.
It is then expected to be available on many other long-distance routes in Germany early next year, "said a railway spokesman.
"Comfort check-in" is what the train calls ticket cancellation without a conductor.
However, in order to be able to use them, a number of prerequisites have to be met: you need a smartphone or tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket - which most passengers do anyway.
You must also have bought it via the DB Navigator app, which is the most convenient way to book tickets anyway.
And last but not least, you need a seat reservation.
This is how the "comfort check-in" works: you board the train and call up your ticket under "My Tickets."
The test customers will then see a button for electronic validation.
The conductors receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y.
When the conductor arrives at seat Y at the ticket inspection, he knows that there is a passenger with an online ticket that has already been validated.
So you can sleep on, keep working, keep quiet.
"Check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn should benefit passengers.
"If you want to travel relaxed without ticket control by our train attendants, simply check in yourself in the DB Navigator.
This enables passengers to personalise their travel time on the train, "says Michael Peterson, Chief Marketing Officer of DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: "And our employees have more time than today to respond to individual customer needs."
Anyone who often travels by train knows that, apart from delays and missed trains, ticket checks are one of the biggest annoyances.
Because often you yourself, but in any case one of the passengers does not have all the documentation you need for the validation of online tickets.
Either the credit card or the identity card or any other document you have to show is missing.
As a result, there are endless discussions between the conductor and the passenger, which leads to a bad atmosphere in the compartment or in the wider area and delays in checking your own ticket, ultimately taking the conductor's time to deal with other concerns.
Only a small number of test customers can still use the new service.
And only on the ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen connections.
Other train numbers on the same route have not yet been unlocked.
How one activist came to learn the answer to the question: "Whose Streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native sat on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone in high school.
"Police have just killed an 18-year-old child and it is still lying on the street," it said.
Confused because no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @ TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was live-tweeting the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body, which was sprawled out in the street and would remain there for four hours.
"That's wild," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later in the evening.
There were photos of police tape and people screaming, and of a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a sign that read, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
She was watching a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer pulled out his gun and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
"It's not common," Ferrell recalled her saying.
'It's not the kind of murder we've become accustomed to and we can call typical. '
At that moment I felt chills.
I was angry and I was crying. "
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?," in theaters March 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, from the point of view of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and matching crown, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before this morning "about the black experience and the black condition."
"You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled saying.
'We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that wasn't right.
I couldn't take them, "Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a culmination of... what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see it and be brought up in it.
It needs to be well developed, to know not only activism and organization, but also the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution and what we need to do to become free, to liberate ourselves.
Even though I am lucky enough to give her an experience where she personally does not experience blatant racism, she is no different from the next black woman's child.
I feel like I'm doing her a disservice by keeping her out of it. '
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place across from the police department that became a camp area as activists waited for Officer Darren Wilson's possible non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and her daughter bonded with a local business owner who made lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to demonstrators.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come together. '
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story you can exploit?"
That skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often whites, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson didn't center their voices, and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had previously worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist known for his activism around death row inmates.
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project, and along with six other locals, the "Whose Streets?" team followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or talks to us, we talk," Davis said.
'That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed. '
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement "is not a Messiah leader, but a community that comes together," Folayan said - but she turned out to be the film's most open participant.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" reveal surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, including how she fell in love and married her wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
'But I've understood that there has to be a certain vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people. '
Ferrell's story also echoes the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders, who shaped the film "BlacklivesMatter" on social media after the 2012 killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin, identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement as a whole," Ferrell said, "and that's why we're constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of it all. "
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being upheld by black women and many black women."
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action," with Ferrell chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up that energy," she said.
'It's no coincidence that she was on the front lines because there's so much at stake in living at these intersections as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen. "
Now the news cameras are long gone in Ferguson, but racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is on probation for 2 ½ years for blocking a highway at a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls her home: "A mess."
Still, she clings to singing, and she's been committed to that memory ever since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains. "
