A fitting similarity: Artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York, there are many faces - white, black, and brown, almost imperceptibly alike - hanging from cables from the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek dabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clips from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence after leaking classified diplomatic cables through the website WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science, and the arts, and Manning, a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose conviction was commuted by Barack Obama when he was just three days into office.
Dewey-Hagborg, through the algorithmic analysis of DNA extracted by Manning, from which 30 portraits of what someone with these genomic data might look like, has created a sharp, if somewhat intellectual commentary not only on the malleability of DNA data - the many ways it can be interpreted, and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since puberty, was convicted in 2013 of 20 charges, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her image was suppressed by prison, so much so that there was only one photo - a grainy black-and-white selfie in which Manning sits visibly uncomfortable in a driver's seat and wears a platinum blonde wig - to which she has been associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg just returned from the huge success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum by extracting DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That was when she received an e-mail from a newspaper magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some kind of portrait to accompany this article," Dewey-Hagborg said at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't be visited at the time and she couldn't be photographed, so you got in touch with Chelsea and asked if she wanted a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became disparate pen friends, exchanging several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic, "Suppressed Images," illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which foresaw a future in which the president would overturn Chelsea's ruling and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would indeed call for Manning's release after seven brutal years in a Kansas military prison just days after the book was published was a welcome sort of happy coincidence.
There is something deep and powerful about the opening of the exhibition, too, as Donald Trump wades into a war against government whistleblowers and transgender troops to find new, tweetable ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to heal.
When asked about the strange timing of all these things, Dewey-Hagborg said that "things happen for a reason."
In an artistic statement written on the gallery wall, Manning called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture" with her oversized signature underneath (the "i" in her surname has a heart).
On the opposite wall is her mitochondrial DNA sequence - a centipede of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
Dewey-Hagborg hoped the inclusion of 200 letters (or nucleotides according to the artist's sophisticated scientific lexicon) would show how astonishingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"What people will hopefully take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective they are," said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Spurious Memories, can also be seen.
'DNA data can tell so many different stories, so that's 30 of those stories. '
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in its own room, is a page from the above-mentioned comic novel.
It shows Manning emerging from the United States military barracks like King Kong with a hands-free phone in hand.
"If they cold-call your speech, they won," it says.
"So never shut up."
"It came straight from a letter she wrote me," said the artist, who hails from Philadelphia.
'I still get goosebumps when I'm talking about it. '
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person - as anticipated presciently in the comic book - but if she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, her own genomic simulacra that cluster like hordes of protesters.
This was purposeful, like everything in the exhibition, down to size (5 "2, Manning's stature), where her genetic haplogroups were written in pencil.
"In the past, I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
'I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was also behind their liberation, 'he said.
