The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to the financial website Let's Talk Payments.
Denver, Colorado, start-up Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid the Uber case in disrepute.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send bespoke "pulse" surveys, collect confidential answers in real time, and view heat maps of your problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text message hotline for employees to report bad behavior.
And if the chief executive is involved, complaints go directly to the supervisory board.
"The court of public opinion has caught up with the regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, the founder and chief executive of Convercent.
If a company is found to treat its employees badly or behave unethically, it can face costly consequences from consumer boycotts, employee turnover and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
