White House Advertising Costs Taxpayers Thousands
The White House's decision to fly a naval helicopter to the South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month cost taxpayers up to $24,000, according to military figures provided to TIME magazine.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of the July 17 event at the White House featuring American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
The White House military office requested the helicopter's presence in a fragmentary order, or QUESTION, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to the records of Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it is such an unusual event with high visibility," the commander of the HMX-1 wrote to his superior, the deputy naval commander for aviation, on the eve of the event.
The message indicated that the helicopter arrived on the South Lawn around 7 a.m. on July 17 for the event at 3 p.m., and stayed until the lawn was cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. that evening.
The note adds that if the departure from the White House were to be delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the restrictions on service hours.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the unit's security personnel remained with the aircraft during the time on the ground.
It was not clear from the records provided to TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event could violate the provision.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were informed that it was not," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're locked up," the deputy commander replied.
The "Made in America" event was designated an official event by the White House and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But official events also have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave a push for health care reform, which was underway in the Senate, and touted efforts to curb government regulation.
The use of the aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for politically beneficial purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to request their use only for a photo op is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was taxiing ahead of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the" Made In America "show - which features products from all 50 states made by American workers using American materials," said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights in the Washington area and on the South Lawn to drop the US President off at the White House with precise centimetres.
When Trump was in Germany for the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight for the "Made in America" event counted toward the flight crew's training needs for the month, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions."
The White House said taxpayers did not shoulder the burden for any of the other props presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in exhibiting the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the DoD reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records the plane's flight time as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility's home base in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far below that rate.
"Establishing the cost to taxpayers on the basis of estimates of reimbursement rates is highly misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance, and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
'The idea is to showcase things that are made in America this week, 'Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud to contribute to our national security, and I expect hundreds, if not thousands, of people to depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly for.
It's obviously appropriate to highlight that. '
It was not clear if Trump interacted with the helicopter as he entered his tour of the South Lawn for the event, but he sat in the driver's seat of a fire engine.
At the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I have three of them."
