Reverse role: The city is hiring 46 kitchen assistants
The city organizes the daycare lunch again itself.
With fixed contact persons for the children and an assignment to the team.
In city daycare centers, the clock is being turned back.
On 1 September, the city of Krefeld will again take over the food supply in the municipal daycare facilities (daycare centers) on its own initiative.
For Sonja Pommeranz, deputy head of the department for youth welfare, this is good news: "We were all very pleased."
Cooking continues outside the house: a caterer takes over this task and delivers freshly cooked and chilled food.
The city operates 46 day care centers in the Krefeld area, in 44 the children get a hot meal at noon.
Last year, 2,800 children sat at tables, and demand is growing steadily.
"In the meantime, not only children, who are cared for 45 hours a week, eat lunch in the kindergarten," Pommeranz explains.
"The offer also applies to 35-hour care if children stay until 2 pm."
From 1 September onwards, 46 part-time staff will be on kitchen duty: they will heat up the food supplied, add lettuce, raw food and fruit to it, portion the meal individually, dispense the food, clean up, rinse and clean the kitchen.
"Employees are firmly assigned to a day care center," Pommeranz says.
Size - there are two-group as well as seven-group institutions - determines the amount of lessons.
"The kitchen assistants are now firmly part of the daycare team," Pommeranz says with satisfaction.
"This way they are much more involved and it is easier for the management to implement pedagogical concepts."
That's what it's all about: healthy eating and cooking classes.
"The children should help to prepare the food."
The direct connection of the kitchen force to the team makes sense.
Also for the children.
"They have a known force in kindergarten, a person who is familiar to them, and not constantly changing people."
This continuity is important for the children.
The cleaning of the daycare rooms - previously also the task of the kitchen staff - will in future be carried out by special cleaning staff.
This variant - the separation of cleaning and kitchen service - not only improves the quality of the kitchen performance, but also has the charm that it has proved to be the most economical for the city in terms of the cost comparison between self-management and outsourcing, according to the press office.
This is despite 46 part-time staff being recruited.
"But these hours are not that important for about 750 people in the education sector," says Sonja Pommeranz.
Afghan democracy depends on women's political role, UN says
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, have a role to play, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the United Nations mission, said hundreds of women will run in provincial council elections, with three women running for vice president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters being women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved in all parts of the electoral process.
Afghan elections for the provincial council and presidential elections will be held on April 5.
The Taliban have issued threats against an election process that coincide with the transition from international combat to an advisory role.
This year, for the first time, the elections will pass peacefully from one democratically elected government to the next.
Haysom said a strong role for women will further enhance Afghanistan's democratic success.
Afghanistan's Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters are registered.
