GMB concerns over investment at Glasgow's McVitie factory
A union is seeking assurances from managers at biscuit maker McVitie about its long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company had remained silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which makes Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits, among other products.
McVitie's owner, Pladis, said he had invested more than £5 million in the last few years.
He added that staff and union representatives would be "the first to know" if their jobs would change.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland called on McVitie's to "raise concerns that funding for the modernisation of production lines is not being taken forward."
GMB senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "The lack of clarity from the general manager about Tollcross's business needs and investment plans for the future is deeply concerning to our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily focused on the local community and Greater Glasgow, an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and in the context of Brexit, rising cost of living and chronic manufacturing decline, the eastern end of Glasgow desperately needs a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie. "
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The branch manager at Tollcross only received a letter from GMB Scotland yesterday and the company will respond immediately as we appreciate the continued engagement of staff and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago where some issues were openly discussed.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we constantly review our business - and this applies to all our divisions and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a manufacturing site. If our operations at the site change, the first people to hear of this will be the employees and their union representatives. "
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar three years ago?
The La Liga side may regret their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not relent in their pursuit of Neymar after making a £189m bid to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona three years ago about a world-record raid?
The sensational approach has fuelled the summer transfer window, with the Ligue 1 club poised to break the world record by more than double the previous mark, with Paul Pogba returning to Manchester United for £89million last season.
Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world and the highest paid professional athlete in the world when he finishes his career, with PSG offering wages in excess of £500,000 a week.
Barcelona are furious at the way Neymar has forced his way out, although a source close to the Catalan executive insists the club have always done their best to look after him since he arrived from Santos in 2013.
But was the world of football warned about this prospect by the PSG president three years ago?
When Manchester City expressed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi had a stern warning for any club wishing to sign one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players then we will be in opposition to them, we will contact their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
'We respect all clubs, 'he said.
But if they try to sign one of our players, there will be consequences. "
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line, with the Spanish club expressing interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear they would not allow the Italy international to leave under any circumstances and Barcelona could feel the effects of that interest by losing one of their bid for Neymar.
