Interview: "Domspatzen Report relieves Pope brother Georg Ratzinger"
The Regensburg Cathedral sparrow report on abuse exonerates the Pope's brother Georg Ratzinger.
Author and historian Michael Hesemann thinks so.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen continues to generate discussion.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman of the reform movement "Wir sind Kirche," told the Deutsche Presse-Agentur after publication that he expected an apology from the former bishop of Regensburg and now Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller as well as from the cathedral bandmaster Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of Pope Emeritus Benedict XVI.
It would greatly serve the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret at their own omissions or their misjudgement of events at the time.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano," on the other hand, criticised the "double standard" applied to the coverage of violence by the Domspatzen.
With regard to the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubts that these are "shameful and shameful acts" that must be punished and prevented in the future, but what is striking is the "degree of media manipulation," according to the author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
"The habit of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evils is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider it normal," Scaraffia writes.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis also said in an interview with Bayerischer Rundfunk: "People like to go to church and that's a feast for the eyes."
She also pointed out that in her youth, "beatings were a perfectly normal educational means of coping with naughty children like me."
She thinks it is unfair to apply today's standards to earlier decades, because the world has changed.
In connection with the reports of the abuse cases pope brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
Quite wrongly, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who with Ratzinger wrote the book of remembrance "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages).
"I have to protect Georg Ratzinger," says Hesemann, "because none of this had anything to do with him," he assesses the conclusions of the final report.
What exactly does the 440-page report by Ulrich Weber, a lawyer commissioned by the Regensburg diocese to investigate the matter, say?
Between 1945 and the beginning of the 1990s, a total of 547 Regensburger Domspatzen were victims of attacks "with high plausibility," while 67 Domspatzen were sexually abused.
In the final report, Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994, is quoted as saying: "In summary, it can be stated that in many cases, forms of physical and psychological violence were used by R. Domkapellmeister.
Particularly with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be more severe.
Nevertheless, unlike many other defendants, it is noticeable that many victims appreciated R. "s general humanity and therefore in many cases, despite violence, they even associate him with positive memories."
In this interview, Hesemann explains why the final report on the abuse scandal at Regensburg Cathedral sparrows exonerates Georg Ratzinger in his opinion.
Mr Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "Incidents of violence against persons subject to protection by the Regensburger Domspatzen" paints a contradictory picture of the cathedral bandmaster Georg Ratzinger.
For one thing, many students emphasize his "humanity."
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist, who often became tangible when a cathedral sparrow did not achieve a top performance musically.
As his biographer, how do you view this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the whole 440-page report from beginning to end, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger appears in it at all.
Only eight pages are devoted to him and he is clearly cleared of any suspicion of complicity or complicity in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of preschool violence also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
At best, he can be accused of having learned about it too late or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, where he worked, was perceived by practically all respondents as - so literally - "redemption," "heaven" and "better world."
The vast majority of his pupils also give Georg Ratzinger an excellent certificate, describing him as "warm-hearted," "popular," "sincere," "competent" and "understanding," as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and who was "always surrounded by grapes from children."
Only a minority complain about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which sometimes led to tantrums.
Years ago, he himself admitted, deeply regretted and apologized for not only banging chairs and throwing the keychain on the floor, but also distributing slaps and pulling too cheeky boys by the hair or ears.
To save his honor, however, it must be said that in the period in question, the 1960 "s and 1970" s, such methods of education were widespread, both among parents and teachers.
Do you know of such methods of chastisement?
Of course, I think every one of us who was born before 1968.
I, too, experienced this in a secular school, a state grammar school.
Compared with what this report is actually about, namely the appalling sexual abuse and violence in pre-school, these are, of course, trivial matters.
One wonders whether it is not more to do with his notoriety and his role as brother of Benedict XVI that many media outlets have pounced on him.
Many who have never understood the Bavarian Pope are still working hard for him.
The truth is, however, that the report exonerates Georg Ratzinger in every respect.
In connection with the report, much has been reported in the media on the subject of abuse at Regensburg Cathedral Sparrows.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused of any involvement or complicity in sexual abuse in the final report?
Michael Hesemann: Definitely no.
Not one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have confided in the cathedral chaplain.
Not even the parents were privy.
"I never dared to talk to my father or my mother about it," one of those affected testified on behalf of the others, "it was all very embarrassing to me."
The real problem in exposing sexual abuse was, and still is, that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not even entrust themselves to their parents and siblings, then certainly not to a choirmaster, who in a professional sense would have been a colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen students rate Ratzinger's role with regard to abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: As one student put it: "With regard to sexual abuse... I don't see... any case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) of all people had timely knowledge and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I think it is... also really absurd to assume that just him... boys have opened themselves up more forcefully or more clearly or even sooner than to their parents, boarding school principals, confidence teachers, etc.
To talk to him about sex... it's unthinkable. '
The report concludes: "It could not be confirmed during the investigation that pupils and / or those around them had confided in him beforehand."
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger is therefore to be acquitted of any complicity.
Nor can he be accused of failing to prevent or prosecute him.
Therefore, there is no reason to associate his good name with these heinous crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
There was a lot to read in the media about the "excesses of violence" of the Regensburger Domspatzen.
The former cathedral bandmaster Georg Ratzinger is accused of "looking the other way" in the report.
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem, that in the reporting everything was mixed up and mixed up to a huge mélange of sexual abuse and violence excesses and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that, in turn, is an abuse of the report.
There is a neat separation between the preschool and the gymnasium of the Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence and, shall we say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the time since 1945, i.e. also from four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not choirmaster of the Domspatzen.
The whole terrible pedagogy of beatings, the cases in which boys were literally harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered terribly, all took place at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But cathedral bandmaster Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he only saw the boys when they were already at the cathedral secondary school.
On this occasion, as the vast majority of witnesses emphasize, the topic of "preschool" was taboo.
They were just happy to have escaped and enjoyed the much better treatment and, for many, even "paradise."
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, for whom the report concludes that "many victims appreciated R." s general humanity and therefore in many cases, despite violence, even associate him with positive memories. "
All that remains is the accusation of having looked the other way.
But despite its best efforts, the report could only define two periods in which it was told about the conditions in preschool.
The first time was in 1970 / 71, when he was just starting to establish himself and did not want to hear about what was happening at a school where he was not working and was responsible (according to the witness), and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because as early as 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it, he points out that "caning continues in preschool."
Faced with the risk of negative press coverage, he recommended urgent action.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when caning had long been prohibited in Bavaria.
Before that, they took place in a legal grey area, as all of us are well aware.
Here, too, it was difficult for him to estimate where those affected might have been exaggerated or dramatised, and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he's always looked the other way.
This is simply not true.
It was not until 1980 that caning in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today's pedagogical standards to the time.
How do you see it?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "pitfall of anachronism," that is, the danger of judging the past according to today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But of course this does not apply to sexual abuse, which was abhorrent at all times, nor to the atrocities and violence committed against innocent children's souls in pre-school, which goes far beyond what was usual at the time.
This is all terrible and I am glad that it is finally being dealt with.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because none of this had anything to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, i.e. slapping and pulling hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was then banned, he adhered strictly to it.
What image of his Regensburg time did Georg Ratzinger reproduce in his conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Did the subject of caning also come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, i.e. Pope Benedict XVI, and tells from his perspective that the Domspatzen only played a supporting role.
Nevertheless, I do not conceal the fact that he led a strict regiment there.
But even this has to be said: without this perfectionism, without demanding absolute discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to transform the hitherto rather nationally known Regensburger Domspatzen into a world-class institution, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, which toured twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and sweets alone, you don't make great singers out of unruly boys and stand before every success, no matter in what field, but always discipline, passion and self-control.
What kind of person did you experience Georg Ratzinger during the discussions on her book?
Michael Hesemann: Through working on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger quite well and experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, fundamentally kind, deeply faithful and kind-hearted person, one cannot imagine that he could do any harm to a fly.
I regularly hear how many former Cathedral Sparrows still maintain regular contact with him 23 years after his retirement, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him like a member of their family.
So those who have not forgiven him for once being strict with them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the Cathedral Sparrows are grateful to him today for enriching their lives and bringing them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, sure, that may be - but also a lovable person of respect to whom they still look up and who they almost revere.
And please, let me be very clear: all he is accused of are the methods of education that were the order of the day back then.
We can be glad that we have come a long way from this time.
But it is highly unfair to make a man a media scapegoat just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
The malicious intent behind this is all too obvious.
The report that has just been published exonerates him.
Now the decency would dictate that a 93-year-old man, who has earned great merit and without whom probably no one outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany would know the Regensburger Domspatzen, should finally be left in peace.
